Ensure your application is running on your EC2 instances. A simple Express.js server might look like this: 
javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello from Node.js on EC2!');
});

// Health check endpoint for the Load Balancer
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.status(200).send('OK');
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`);
});
2. Configure Security Groups
You need two security groups for proper communication: 

ALB Security Group: Allow inbound traffic on port 80 (and 443 if using SSL) from 0.0.0.0/0.
EC2 Security Group: Allow inbound traffic on your app's port (e.g., 3000) only from the ALB Security Group to ensure users can't bypass the load balancer. 
3. Create a Target Group
Navigate to the Target Groups section in the EC2 Console.
Choose Instances as the target type.
Set the Protocol to HTTP and Port to 3000 (or your app's port).
Configure Health Checks: Use the /health path created in your app code.
Register your running EC2 instances as targets. 
